<br>
If they are doing it this way, then their changes are going to be results-oriented, meaning that they are going to tweak until they get the results they want as opposed to making a few calculations and doing a change they predict will have the results they want and going with that.  If they do it this way, we are not going to like it, I guarantee it, unless they totally screw it up and the screw-up happens to go in our favor hehehehe.<br>
<br>
The mechanics of the game are kind of complicated and a change that gives them the results they want under one set of circumstances might give entirely different results under other circumstances.  For example, suppose they used a level 45 monk in average gear to run the tests and tweaked him until he was 10% worse at tanking level 45 monsters by adjusting his avoidance/mitigation.  Those same adjustments might make a level 60 monk in good gear 10% better at tanking his typical xp mob (level 55 or so), or they might make a monk better at tanking extremely high level monsters (65, 70, 75).  With any luck, we'll end up better off than we were before.  I'll laugh my butt off if that happens.<br>
